		<h4><div>Get your<br>eclectic on</div></h4>
		<p>Guest conductor Judith Yan will have her hands full with Michael Nyby (baritone), Xiao-Nan Wang (Chinese fl ute) and the varied repertoire for this exciting concert of mostly new music.</p>
		<p>Winnipeggers first: composer Jim Hiscott penned the refl ective Far Heavens with musical collaborator Xiao-Nan Wang in mind (aficionados will remember our 2009 performance of Xiao-Nan Wang&rsquo;s <i>Camel Train in the Desert</i>, arranged then by Hiscott.</p>
		<p>Then there&rsquo;s <i>Five enerations &mdash; one house</i>, a piece which composer Julian Grant was inspired to write after receiving a gift of a butterfly harp (yangqin) while living in Beijing. The yangqin led to a guzheng, then a piano led to the strings, which is where we come in!</p>
		<p>An operatic element is introduced when baritone Michael Nyby sings <i>200 Dreams from Captivity</i>, composed by American composer Scott Wheeler. Wheeler, based in Boston, specializes in vocal
		and dramatic music.</p>
		<p><b>Judith Yan can handle eclectic</b></p>
		<p>Judith Yan is currently the Artistic Director of Guelph Symphony Orchestra and the Music Director and Principal Conductor of Opera on the Avalon. She has been a staff conductor for the San Francisco Opera, the Canadian Opera Company and the National Ballet.</p>
		<p>&ldquo;The evening&rsquo;s principal hero was conductor Judith Yan, who led this daunting score with astonishing precision and fluency ...&rdquo; (Joshua Kosman, <i>San Francisco Chronicle</i>).</p>

