			<div class="tab-pane fade" id="bios">
				<p><b>Judith Yan</b></p>
				<p>Judith Yan is the Artistic Director of Guelph Symphony Orchestra and Music Director and Principal Conductor of Opera on the Avalon, a summer festival in St. John&rsquo;s, Newfoundland. She has been a Staff Conductor for the San Francisco Opera, the Canadian Opera Company, and the National Ballet of Canada.</p>
				<p>As a conductor of ballet, she has led over 90 performances at the Four Season&rsquo;s Centre for the National Ballet of Canada. Since 2010, she has had a close association with Hong Kong Ballet, conducting the company&rsquo;s productions of <i>Sleeping Beauty</i>, <i>Swan Lake</i>, and <i>The Nutcracker</i>.</p>
				<p>With the San Francisco Opera, she served as Staff Conductor, assistant to Maestro Donald Runnicles. While at SFO, her performance of Stravinsky&rsquo;s <i>The Rake&rsquo;s Progress</i> for San Francisco Opera (Merola) was included in the San Francisco Chronicle&rsquo;s &lsquo;Top Ten Classical Performances of the Year.&rsquo; She made her company debut with Mozart&rsquo;s <i>La Finta Giardiniera</i>.</p>
				<p>Prior to San Francisco Opera, she served as the first Conductor-in-Residence of the Canadian Opera Company. She made her German conducting debut at Ulmer Oper with <i>La Cenerentola</i> and <i>Idomeneo</i>, and her Italian debut in 2007 in Sulmona, Italy with Mozart&rsquo;s <i>Le Nozze di Figaro</i>. She returned in 2008 to conduct Puccini&rsquo;s <i>La Boh&egrave;me</i>. Recent guest engagements include the Hong Kong Philharmonic, Pacific North West Ballet, Stratford Symphony, and the Auckland Philharmonia Orchestra in New Zealand.</p>
				<p>The 2013/14 season includes concerts with Guelph Symphony Orchestra, a new production of <i>Don Quixote</i> for Hong Kong Ballet, and Puccini&rsquo;s <i>La Boh&egrave;me</i> and a gala concert with Opera on the Avalon, where she returns for her fifth season as Music Director and Principal Conductor.</p>
				<p><b>Michael Nyby</b></p>
				<p>A native of Hamilton, Ontario, Michael Nyby holds a bachelor&rsquo;s degree in voice performance from Ithaca College, where he was a student of Randie Blooding, and a Master&rsquo;s in opera from the University of British Columbia, where he studied with Peter Barcza. He made his operatic debut in 2002 with the Ithaca Opera Company, and his Canadian professional debut in 2007 with the Burnaby Lyric Opera. He has performed with the Vancouver Opera, the Vancouver Bach Choir, the Santa Fe Opera, Minnesota Opera, Opera Atelier, the Toronto Mendelssohn Choir, Theatre Aquarius, the Caramoor Festival, and the Duluth Festival Opera. Michael was a member of the 2007/08 Vancouver Opera in Schools touring ensemble with whom he sang 138 performances of Rossini&rsquo;s <i>Figaro</i>. He has participated in artist development programs such as the Santa Fe Opera Apprentice program, the Minnesota Opera Resident Artist Program, and the Vancouver Opera Young Artist Coaching Intensive. When not performing, Michael resides in Toronto with his wife and two cats.</p>
				<p><b>Xiao-Nan Wang</b></p>
				<p>Xiao-Nan Wang began his study of the Chinese bamboo flute at age 11. He was an instructor at the Department of Music at the Inner Mongolia Normal College where he taught flute, music theory and Chinese folk music history.</p>
				<p>Xiao-Nan immigrated to Winnipeg in 1995, and soon established himself as a master of the Chinese bamboo flute. In 2003, he was invited to appear in the movie <i>The Saddest Music in the World</i>, produced by Guy Maddin, in which he played a talented musician. In March 2004, he performed in a concert sponsored by CBC Radio and the Folk Art Council of Canada, also entitled <i>The Saddest Music in the World</i>. In 2005, the Winnipeg Symphony Orchestra commissioned local composer Jim Hiscott to write a concerto for Xiao-Nan. This piece, entitled <i>North Wind</i>, was premiered by Xiao-Nan in the 2006 Winnipeg New Music Festival. Gwenda Nemerofsky, the music critic for the <i>Winnipeg Free Press</i>, commented that &ldquo;Xiao-Nan&rsquo;s performance was the highlight of the evening.&rdquo;</p>
				<p>In the spring of 2007, Xiao-Nan returned to China to complete modifications of the Chinese bamboo flute. He called this new instrument the &lsquo;Chromatic Flute.&rsquo; He would like to record a number of CDs with this new instrument. Xiao-Nan&rsquo;s artistic vision is to explore new musical ideas and create new music for his instrument. He wishes to combine the old and the new, fuse the East and the West, and raise bamboo flute playing technique to new heights. </p>
				<p>Xiao-Nan has since performed with the Manitoba Chamber Orchestra, the Winnipeg Philharmonic Choir, and many other groups. In his private time, he is constantly modifying his flute to suit the music he plays. His newest flute has 10 holes and a mouth-piece. He is anxious to accept students who are interested in learning his art.</p>
				<p><b>Julian Grant</b></p>
				<p>Julian Grant is a composer, writer, educator, music journalist, and broadcaster. He was born in London in 1960, lived in Asia for many years and, since 2010, has resided in Princeton and New York. He has composed 18 operas, which have been performed by the English National Opera, The Royal Opera, Almeida Opera, Mecklenburgh Opera, and T&ecirc;te-&agrave;-T&ecirc;te. <i>The Skin Drum</i> (1988) won the National Opera Association of America&rsquo;s New Opera prize and <i>Out of Season</i> (1991) was nominated for an Olivier Award. He writes extensively on opera, Russian music, and contemporary music for many music journals.</p>
				<p>From 2002 to 2007, he was director of music at St. Paul&rsquo;s Girls&rsquo; School in London, a post previously occupied by Gustav Holst, Vaughan-Williams and Herbert Howells. He has worked for Hong Kong University, hosted a radio show for RTHK, and has been involved in education work for London&rsquo;s major opera houses, including an extensive tour of Russia in 1990 with English National Opera. He worked extensively with the Beijing New Music Ensemble, and studied the Yang-Qin (Butterfly Harp) while living in China. From 2010 to 2013 he was Composer in Residence at Saint Ann&rsquo;s School, Brooklyn. A long-term relationship with the experimental opera company T&ecirc;te-&agrave;-T&ecirc;te has yielded several miniature works: <i>Platform 10</i>, <i>Odd Numbers</i>, <i>Anger</i> and <i>Only Connect</i>. A full-length work, <i>Odysseus Unwound</i>, toured Britain and Europe in 2006-7, featuring traditional spinners, weavers and knitters from Fair Isle among the performers, and was featured on BBC&rsquo;s <i>The Culture Show</i>. A dance opera, <i>Hot House</i>, produced by TV&rsquo;s <i>The Choir&rsquo;s</i> Gareth Malone, was commissioned for the Cultural Olympiad in London and performed at the Royal Opera House in July 2012. His collected songs and an album of piano works, <i>Shivereens</i>, were recently published. Other works include <i>Great Game</i> for orchestra, <i>Off Course</i> for piano and ensemble and a host of chamber pieces.</p>
				<p>A choral work commemorating the 10th anniversary of 9/11 &mdash; <i>In a Fog &mdash; Remember</i> &mdash; was commissioned by the Grace and Spiritus Chorale of Brooklyn. <i>Dances in the Dark</i>, a new orchestral piece, premieres March 2014 with the Princeton Symphony Orchestra,</p>
				<p>He is currently working with librettist Mark Campbell on an opera for Music Theatre Projects, Brooklyn.</p>
				<p><b>Scott Wheeler</b></p>
				<p>Scott Wheeler has received commissions and performances from the orchestras of Minnesota, Houston, Toledo and Indianapolis, as well as New York City Opera, sopranos Ren&eacute;e Fleming and Lauren Flanigan, baritone Sanford Sylvan, and the Chamber Music Society of Lincoln Center. His opera <i>Democracy: An American Comedy</i>, on a libretto of Romulus Linney, was commissioned and premiered by the Washington National Opera. His chamber symphony <i>City of Shadows</i> was commissioned by Kent Nagano and Deutsches Symphonie-Orchestra Berlin and premiered by them on a portrait concert of the music of Scott Wheeler at the Kammermusiksaal of the Berlin Philharmonie. His compositions are on several labels, including the Naxos American Classics series (&lsquo;Songs for Voice and Piano&rsquo; entitled <i>Wasting the Night</i> and his opera <i>The Construction of Boston</i>).</p>
				<p>Scott Wheeler&rsquo;s most recent commission is for an opera for the Metropolitan Opera and Lincoln Center Theatre. Other current and recent commissions include the Mirror Visions Ensemble, Boston Cecilia, the Rockport Chamber Music Festival, the Marilyn Horne Foundation, the ASCAP Foundation, the Barlow Foundation, and Concert Artists Guild.</p>
				<p>There are two recordings of Scott Wheeler&rsquo;s music on the Naxos American Classics series. The latest of these is a CD of songs for voice and piano, entitled <i>Wasting the Night</i>. The first Naxos disc is of the one-act opera <i>The Construction of Boston</i>. The Gramercy Trio and friends have recorded a disc of Scott&rsquo;s music for strings and piano on Newport Classic. Other recordings are available on GM, New World and Bridge labels.</p>
				<p>As a conductor, Scott Wheeler has appeared with Deutsches Symphonie-Orchestra Berlin, the Chamber Ensemble of St. Luke&rsquo;s in New York, the Wellesley Composers Conference, and Dinosaur Annex. At Emerson College, Wheeler has also conducted productions of the musical theatre works of Leonard Bernstein, Kurt Weill, George Gershwin, Stephen Sondheim, and many others.</p>
				<p>Scott Wheeler studied at Amherst College, New England Conservatory and Brandeis University and, later, at the Tanglewood Music Center (with Olivier Messiaen), the Dartington School (with Peter Maxwell Davies) and privately with Virgil Thomson. He teaches at Emerson College in Boston, where he co-directs the BFA program in musical theatre. He is a founding member of the new-music ensemble Dinosaur Annex.</p>
				<p>He has received many and repeated awards and commissions from, amongst others, the National Endowment for the Arts, the American Academy of Arts and Letters and the Chamber Music Society of Lincoln Center. He was a Distinguished Visitor at the American Academy in Berlin in 2007 and received the Composer of the Year Award from the Classical Recording Foundation.</p>
				<p>Scott Wheeler is on the Board of the Virgil Thomson Foundation and the Education Board of the Youth Orchestra of the Americas.</p>
				<p><b>Jim Hiscott</b></p>
				<p>Jim Hiscott studied composition with Samuel Dolin and David Lidov. He is the recipient of the Creative Arts Award of the Canadian Federation of University Women. His compositions have been performed across North America, in Europe and Asia by many artists including the Hilliard Ensemble, the St. Lawrence String Quartet, the Molinari String Quartet, the Winnipeg Symphony Orchestra, the Montreal Symphony Orchestra, the Edmonton Symphony, Vancouver New Music, Orquesta Joven de Andalusia, the Orpheus Winds, Arraymusic, and Philadelphia&rsquo;s Relâche.</p>
				<p>Hiscott has performed his own works for button accordion in the Winnipeg Symphony Orchestra&rsquo;s New Music Festival, with Vancouver New Music and the Winnipeg Chamber Music Society, and on the main stage of the Vancouver Folk Music Festival. He has appeared as soloist with the Montreal Symphony Orchestra, the Niagara Symphony, and the Winnipeg Symphony Orchestra.</p>
				<p>Recent premieres of music by Jim Hiscott include <i>Ca&ntilde;a</i> for Latin ensemble, string trio and button accordion (Papa Mambo Ensemble, Mary Lawton, Elise Lavall&eacute;e, Emma Quackenbush and Jim Hiscott); <i>Cantu</i> for orchestra (WSO, conductor Alexander Mickelthwate), <i>Pater Noster</i> for SATB choir (Camerata Nova); <i>After Sorrow</i> for string trio (Karl Stobbe, Elise Lavall&eacute;e and Emma Quackenbush), and <i>The Song of the Stars</i> for soprano, guitar and strings (Maria-Luz Alvarez, Rodrigo Mu&ntilde;oz, and the Manitoba Chamber Orchestra, conductor Scott Yoo). Other recent performances include: <i>Shadow Play</i> for flute and tabla (Marie-H&eacute;l&egrave;ne Breault and Shawn Mativetsky; Maison symphonique de Montr&eacute;al, Place des Arts, Montr&eacute;al); <i>Ceremony III</i> for chamber ensemble (Ensemble Musica Nova, conductor Jack Fortner; Musica Nova Festival, S&atilde;o Paulo, Brazil); and <i>Tropics</i> for orchestra (Youth Orchestra of Andalusia, conductor Michael Thomas; Malaga Contemporary Music Festival, Spain).</p>
				<p>String Quartet No. 2 from his CBC Records CD <i>Blue Ocean / Music of Jim Hiscott</i> was nominated for Outstanding Classical Composition at the 2004 Western Canadian Music Awards.</p>

			</div>
			<div class="tab-pane fade" id="notes">
				<p><b>&#20116;&#20195;&#21516;&#22530; / Wu Dai Tong Tang<br>(Five Generations &mdash; One House)<br>Julian Grant</b></p>
				<p><i>The composer has written the following note:</i></p>
				<p>During the time I lived in Beijing, from 2007 to 2010, I was bought, as a consolation prize for not mastering Mandarin, a yang-qin (butterfly harp), because I had admired it in a shop window. The sight of such a handsome instrument residing at home, unplayed, was a reproach, and so I got a very rigorous teacher who taught me the basics, so I was able to play duets with her, and later even joined in with a traditional ensemble. Strangely, it is the one stable instrument of a Chinese opera band that probably originated in eastern Europe, as it resembles a dulcimer. For a family birthday, I managed to compose and play a piece for my yang-qin, which I later transcribed for piano. I surrounded the piece with satellite pieces, using similar restricted pitches and textures, rather like Erik Satie&rsquo;s <i>Gymnop&eacute;dies</i>, to create a small suite. The pieces were composed haphazardly and in no particular order. Because I ended up with five, I allude in the title to the strange inedible fruit, that resembles a lemon with five fingers &mdash; or an inflated rubber glove &mdash; that appears at Chinese New Year: <i>Wu Dai Tong Tang: five generations one house</i> &mdash; here, five aspects of the same material.</p>
				<p>Later, I transcribed the whole piece for string quartet, and then reworked the material for this string orchestra version, which incorporates new music from an abandoned orchestra piece. So even though the five movements remain, the string orchestra piece is slightly more varied and dramatic. The original yang-qin piece is the third movement, and the simple song-like material is the basis for the whole work. Only in the fifth piece is there a notable change in tonality, though it is firmly anchored to the whole by an unchanging refrain. The whole piece lasts 15 minutes.</p>
				<p><b>200 Dreams from Captivity<br>Scott Wheeler</b></p>
				<p><i>The composer has written the following note:</i></p>
				<p><i>200 Dreams from Captivity</i> is an orchestral song cycle for baritone with obbligato cello; the poems are by Wang Dan, a leader of the Chinese democracy movement. Written in Chinese and translated into English by Shalin Liu and Scott Wheeler, all but one of these poems was written while the poet was imprisoned for his role in the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests. The poems are not depictions of life in prison, nor do they explicitly discuss the political issues that brought the poet to this captivity. Rather, this is a series of meditations on memory and friendship, building to a statement of hope in the future. </p>
				<p>The music quotes from two Chinese melodies. <i>Piao ling de luo hua</i> (The faded flowers blowing in the wind) underlies the opening cello solo. <i>The Wild Lilies of Spring</i> is referred to in the poem of that name. Other Chinese references in the music are incidental results of my interest in Chinese music and culture, and have no specific relationship to the text. <i>200 Dreams From Captivity</i> was commissioned through the kind generosity of Shalin Liu. It is dedicated to human dignity and the beauty of spiritual freedom. Much of the work was composed on a generous fellowship from the MacDowell Colony.</p>
				<p><b>Far Heavens<br>Jim Hiscott</b></p>
				<p><i>The composer has written the following note:</i></p>
				<p><i>Far Heavens</i> for chromatic dizi and strings is inspired by Xiao-Nan Wang&rsquo;s spiritual world. It is written for Xiao-Nan&rsquo;s dizi, an instrument that he has transformed from a diatonic bamboo flute to a chromatic instrument made of resin compound. The instrument keeps the many traditional ornaments and glissandi, but adds the extra notes and possibilities of the chromatic scale. There is a feeling of a journey in the piece, although abstracted &mdash; no specific references. The journey is inspired by Xiao-Nan&rsquo;s own life, a path inspired by spirituality, but in physical terms moving through childhood poverty, a rise through the musical hierarchy of the Chinese Army, time spent in Northwest China and Southeast Asia, political tensions in his homeland, moving to Canada, and his devotion through all this to adapting his dizi and music to his new home. <i>Far Heavens</i> was written as part of a Major Arts Grant from the Manitoba Arts Council, and is dedicated to Xiao-Nan Wang.</p>
				<p><b>Serenade for Strings in E Minor, Op. 20<br>Sir Edward Elgar</b></p>
				<p>Numerous front-rank British composers, including Vaughan Williams, Britten, and Holst, have found writing for the rich, expressive and flexible medium of the string orchestra a highly congenial practice. Elgar&rsquo;s contributions were small in number but substantial in every other sense. When fellow composer Herbert Howells asked him for the secret of his understanding of strings, Elgar replied, &ldquo;Study old Handel. I went to him for help ages ago.&rdquo;</p>
				<p>This lovely, warm-hearted Serenade was Elgar&rsquo;s first work for string orchestra. It was followed by the <i>Introduction and Allegro</i> (1905), <i>Elegy</i> (1909), and <i>Sospiri</i> (1914). Its origins appear to lie in three pieces, dating from 1888, the manuscript of which has disappeared. The premiere most likely took place in May 1888, with the Reverend Edward Vine Hall conducting the Worcestershire Musical Union. At that stage, the movements bore titles: <i>Spring Song</i>, <i>Elegy</i>, and <i>Finale</i>. &ldquo;I like ‘em, (the first thing I ever did),&rdquo; Elgar told a friend, Dr. Charles Buck, later that year. </p>
				<p>He revised and re-titled the three pieces in the spring of 1892, in time to offer what he then called <i>Serenade</i> as a third anniversary present to his wife, Alice. The first performance of that version was probably given by the Ladies&rsquo; Orchestral Class in Worcester, an ensemble which Elgar trained and conducted. In later life, he often referred to the <i>Serenade</i> as his favourite among his works. </p>
				<p>The first complete performance by a professional ensemble was given in Antwerp, Belgium in 1896. At first, British audiences greeted the <i>Serenade</i> with indifference. It remained unheard in London until 1906, when Elgar conducted it himself. It has three brief movements, two compact, animated sections framing the heart of the work, a haunting Larghetto. </p>
				<p>Author Michael Kennedy wrote that together with the stirring concert overture, Froissart (1890), the <i>Serenade</i> shows &ldquo;that Elgar was already a master of the orchestra, rare in English music, that he lived and breathed the orchestra as naturally as the air around him, and that, given the spur of the chance of performance in a suitable setting, this kind of music was already within his power.&rdquo;</p>
				<p>Words of wisdom from Herbert Howells: &ldquo;Sonority it is &mdash; sonority without noise &mdash; which is the greatest abiding power of the string medium. In a world of sounding brass and tinkling cymbal, and of noise magnified to the nth degree, this is it &mdash; sonority without noise &mdash; that marks the supreme contribution made by string music to the fund of our musical enchantment.”</p>

